Sure! Here is a function in JavaScript that takes an array of 5 numbers as input and checks if any of the numbers is a valid prime number. If it is, it prints the number to the console.

```javascript
function isPrime(num) {
    if (num <= 1) {
        return false;
    }
    for (let i = 2; i <= Math.sqrt(num); i++) {
        if (num % i === 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
}

function checkPrimes(arr) {
    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
        if (isPrime(arr[i])) {
            console.log(arr[i]);
        }
    }
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10];
checkPrimes(numbers);
```

In this function, `isPrime` checks if a number is prime by testing if it is divisible by any number from 2 to the square root of the number. If it is divisible, it returns false; otherwise, it returns true.

The `checkPrimes` function iterates through the array and uses `isPrime` to check each number. If a number is prime, it prints the number to the console.

