To remove an item from an array in JavaScript, you can use the `remove` method. Here's a simple example:

```javascript
let array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
array.remove(3); // Removes the element with value 3
console.log(array); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

If you want to remove multiple elements from the array, you can use a loop:

```javascript
let array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
for (let i = 0; i < array.length; i++) {
    if (array[i]!== 3) {
        array.splice(i, 1);
    }
}
console.log(array); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

If you want to remove an element by its index, you can use the `pop` method:

```javascript
let array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
array.pop();
console.log(array); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

If you want to remove an element by its value, you can use the `filter` method:

```javascript
let array = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
array.filter(item => item!== 3);
console.log(array); // Output: [1, 2, 4, 5]
```

These are some of the most common ways to remove an item from an array in JavaScript.

